the excitement over,

236
00:20:25,463 --> 00:20:27,291
we sat down to dinner.

237
00:20:27,326 --> 00:20:31,700
It was then, that
I noticed Harriet wasn’t there.

238
00:20:32,581 --> 00:20:37,160
And she wasn’t there the next
morning.  Or the next.

239
00:20:37,195 --> 00:20:39,539
Or the next forty years.

240
00:20:42,579 --> 00:20:45,527
What was she going to tell me?  Why
didn’t I make time for her?

241
00:20:45,562 --> 00:20:47,135
Why didn’t I listen?

242
00:20:47,673 --> 00:20:50,906
- And she couldn’t have run away?
- Not without being seen.

243
00:20:51,377 --> 00:20:53,648
Firemen stayed
on the bridge all night

244
00:20:53,683 --> 00:20:55,024
pumping out the gasoline.

245
00:20:55,059 --> 00:20:57,271
And no one swam across,
or took a row boat.

246
00:20:57,306 --> 00:21:00,379
All of them were still tied up
on this side Sunday.

247
00:21:00,954 --> 00:21:03,613
Believe me,
I checked.

248
00:21:05,917 --> 00:21:07,387
She couldn’t have just
fallen and drowned?

249
00:21:07,422 --> 00:21:09,227
Oh, no. The currents
aren’t strong here.

250
00:21:09,262 --> 00:21:12,104
Anything that falls into the water
turns up nearby.

251
00:21:12,639 --> 00:21:14,178
Like her father.

252
00:21:14,213 --> 00:21:16,548
His body didn’t drift more
than ten meters

253
00:21:16,583 --> 00:21:19,370
when he drowned
the year before.

254
00:21:19,405 --> 00:21:21,836
No. No. Someone killed her,

255
00:21:22,717 --> 00:21:25,442
Someone on the island
that day.

256
00:21:25,477 --> 00:21:29,816
Someone close enough to know
what she used to give me each year

257
00:21:29,851 --> 00:21:31,980
on my birthday.

258
00:21:33,975 --> 00:21:35,339
Those were from her.

259
00:21:36,814 --> 00:21:39,557
The rest...from her killer.

260
00:21:53,180 --> 00:21:56,971
- Who knows about these?
- Just me, the police, the killer...

261
00:21:58,417 --> 00:21:59,958
and now you.

262
00:22:08,591 --> 00:22:10,904
After, the police investigation evaporated,

263
00:22:10,939 --> 00:22:14,408
I kept at it -
studying all the information there was,

264
00:22:14,443 --> 00:22:18,409
I’ve spent half my life
examining the events of a single day.

265
00:22:18,444 --> 00:22:20,745
I understand your frustration, But...

266
00:22:20,780 --> 00:22:23,702
what you’re asking me to do is
a waste of money

267
00:22:23,703 --> 00:22:25,316
We haven’t discussed your fee.

268
00:22:25,317 --> 00:22:26,618
We don’t need to.

269
00:22:26,619 --> 00:22:27,996
Thank you.

270
00:22:28,730 --> 00:22:32,187
I can’t find something you haven’t
been able to  in forty years.

271
00:22:32,222 --> 00:22:33,675
You don’t know that.

272
00:22:33,710 --> 00:22:36,965
You have a
very keen investigative mind.

273
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:38,354
Here’s what I propose:

274
00:22:38,389 --> 00:22:43,362
You come stay on the island. I have a nice little
cottage by the water you can use.

275
00:22:43,759 --> 00:22:48,268
You study the material I give you.
You find something I’ve missed- or you don’t.

276
00:22:48,303 --> 00:22:51,221
What you're asking me to do
is set aside my life and career....

277
00:22:51,256 --> 00:22:53,601
Think of it as a well
deserved holiday.

278
00:22:53,636 --> 00:22:58,120
A way of avoiding all the
people you want to avoid right now.

279
00:22:58,545 --> 00:23:02,994
As for compensation, I’ll pay you double
your salary for as many months as it takes.

280
00:23:03,029 --> 00:23:05,205
I’ll quadruple it if
you solve the mystery.

281
00:23:05,206 --> 00:23:06,573
- Herr Vanger.
- I’m not done.

282
00:23:06,574 --> 00:23:08,027
I’ll throw in one  more thing -

283
00:23:08,062 --> 00:23:10,227
even though you’re a
terrible negotiator.

284
00:23:10,681 --> 00:23:15,504
It’s something you want more than anything else
and it can’t be bought at any price.

285
00:23:15,539 --> 00:23:20,918
So, let me give it to you ...
Hans-Erik Wennerstrom.

286
00:23:21,599 --> 00:23:23,883
He began his career working for me.

287
00:23:23,918 --> 00:23:27,366
And I’ve followed it with interest,
shall we say, ever since.

288
00:23:30,770 --> 00:23:32,355
You were right about him.

289
00:23:32,859 --> 00:23:34,864
You just couldn’t prove it.

290
00:24:05,886 --> 00:24:08,772
We’re in the middle of our worst crisis ever
and you’re writing a memoir?

291
00:24:08,807 --> 00:24:10,637
You fired me;
I need something to do.

292
00:24:10,672 --> 00:24:12,265
You fired you;

293
00:24:15,089 --> 00:24:17,143
I need you here,
not the North Pole.

294
00:24:17,179 --> 00:24:18,849
Mikael, You know what this
is going to look like.

295
00:24:19,885 --> 00:24:22,112
Like I’ve been gutted.  Like I’m
running away.  I am.

296
00:24:22,147 --> 00:24:24,892
Wennerström wants to see me waving
a white flag, not a red one.

297
00:24:24,927 --> 00:24:27,855
The more it looks like there’s a problem
between you and me, the more it’ll satisfy him.

298
00:24:27,890 --> 00:24:31,474
There is a problem between us.  He
won’t be satisfied until he shuts us down,

299
00:24:33,109 --> 00:24:34,659
You’re leaving me to fight him alone?

300
00:24:34,660 --> 00:24:36,249
It’s four hours by train.

301
00:24:42,329 --> 00:24:44,002
It’s not the North Pole.

302
00:25:26,275 --> 00:25:27,677
Hey, hey.

303
00:26:25,235 --> 00:26:28,138
<i>The network is busy,
please try again later.</i>

304
00:26:39,102 --> 00:26:41,866
<i>The network is busy,
please try again later.</i>

305
00:26:48,620 --> 00:26:49,921
What?

306
00:26:50,674 --> 00:26:52,053
Want some Milk?

307
00:27:10,798 --> 00:27:13,550
<i>The network is busy,
please try again later.</i>

308
00:27:56,398 --> 00:27:57,699
You are Palmgren's daughter?

309
00:27:57,734 --> 00:27:59,543
His ward,
He doesn't have a daughter.

310
00:28:01,528 --> 00:28:02,994
Please.

311
00:28:04,631 --> 00:28:06,952
He's had a severe
cerebral hemorrhaging.

312
00:28:07,390 --> 00:28:10,306
Either from the fall itself,
or a stroke that led to the fall.

313
00:28:11,213 --> 00:28:13,113
His blood pressure is too high.

314
00:28:13,148 --> 00:28:15,921
I’m hopeful he’ll regain consciousness,
but that’s not assured.

315
00:28:16,391 --> 00:28:18,772
And it’s possible, even if he does,

316
00:28:18,807 --> 00:28:21,193
there will be
neurological damage.

317
00:28:50,189 --> 00:28:52,112
Hi, I’m Gunner.

318
00:28:52,677 --> 00:28:53,980
The caretaker.

319
00:28:54,015 --> 00:28:55,524
Oh, hey, Gunnar.

320
00:29:11,996 --> 00:29:13,713
You’re an author?

321
00:29:13,748 --> 00:29:16,894
Well, I'm doing a biography
on Herr Vanger.

322
00:29:19,704 --> 00:29:22,066
- I saw you on television.
- That’s unfortunate.

323
00:29:23,180 --> 00:29:24,481
Bit of trouble, I guess.

324
00:29:25,982 --> 00:29:27,906
No jail time, though.
That’s good.

325
00:29:29,266 --> 00:29:30,938
Cost you a lot of money though, yeah?

326
00:29:33,603 --> 00:29:34,905
There.

327
00:29:34,906 --> 00:29:35,907
It's good.

328
00:29:38,254 --> 00:29:41,986
The entire island is
owned by my family.

329
00:29:44,195 --> 00:29:49,049
Your closest neighbor is
my brother

330
00:29:49,084 --> 00:29:53,954
Harald, another Nazi if you can believe.
Two  in the family.

331
00:29:54,551 --> 00:29:58,229
Oh, yes. He’s quite detestable
to put it nicely,

332
00:29:58,851 --> 00:30:01,826
but you’ll probably never see him.
He’s a recluse.

333
00:30:02,477 --> 00:30:04,653
- He was there that day?
- Indeed, he was.

334
00:30:05,484 --> 00:30:08,227
His daughter, Cecilia,
lives over there.

335
00:30:09,392 --> 00:30:10,751
They don’t speak.

336
00:30:10,786 --> 00:30:13,039
Does anyone speak to
anyone on this island?

337
00:30:13,558 --> 00:30:17,797
Isabella, Harriet’s mother
- who lives there - she speaks to Harald -

338
00:30:17,832 --> 00:30:20,333
which is one of reasons
I don’t speak to her

339
00:30:21,682 --> 00:30:25,244
Cecilia’s brother Birger
lives there.

340
00:30:25,279 --> 00:30:27,867
- Who doesn’t he speak to?
- You, probably.

341
00:30:27,902 --> 00:30:31,984
Not that you’d want him to.
He can be as unpleasant as Harald.

342
00:30:32,019 --> 00:30:33,788
I’m quickly losing
track of who’s who, here.

343
00:30:34,643 --> 00:30:36,419
Oh, how you’ll wish
it were always so.

344
00:30:36,454 --> 00:30:40,714
Soon you’ll know us all only too
well - with my apologies.

345
00:30:41,366 --> 00:30:46,683
Out there is my nephew Martin’s
house; Harriet’s brother.

346
00:30:46,718 --> 00:30:49,100
- Who speaks to him?
- I speak to him.

347
00:30:49,135 --> 00:30:51,899
He runs the company
now, as I think I told you.

348
00:30:54,391 --> 00:30:57,492
Someone shooting their dinner.
Gunner probably.

349
00:30:57,493 --> 00:30:58,795
Oh yes, I met him earlier.

350
00:30:58,796 --> 00:31:01,603
He was 19 when
Harriet disappeared.

351
00:31:03,795 --> 00:31:05,096
He lives over there.

352
00:31:06,989 --> 00:31:08,779
- And you live there?
- Sorry?

353
00:31:08,814 --> 00:31:10,115
Your house.

354
00:31:11,758 --> 00:31:13,824
Oh, yes!

355
00:31:15,240 --> 00:31:16,902
Yes, you’re right.

356
00:31:16,937 --> 00:31:21,676
The man who  hires the detective should
always bekept on the suspects list.

357
00:33:23,066 --> 00:33:26,659
<font color="#3399FF">DET. MORELL:</font> The fact that
I never found a body  was not surprising.

358
00:33:26,694 --> 00:33:28,894
You can’t dig  up an entire island.

359
00:33:30,836 --> 00:33:36,015
But neither could I find the motive.
Was it spontaneous? Was it calculated?

360
00:33:36,050 --> 00:33:38,419
Did she know something someone
wished she didn’t?

361
00:33:38,454 --> 00:33:41,901
-  Was it about business?
- Business?  But she was sixteen.

362
00:33:41,936 --> 00:33:43,478
And very bright.

363
00:33:44,131 --> 00:33:49,327
Henrik told me he could easily see her
running the business one day,

364
00:33:49,362 --> 00:33:52,046
She was with some friends that day.
At a parade.

365
00:33:52,081 --> 00:33:55,473
She told them she was  feeling unwell.
She left early

366
00:33:55,967 --> 00:33:59,794
But they also told me
she kept secrets from them, too.

367
00:33:59,829 --> 00:34:03,251
The main thing I learned was that
teenage girls are complicated.

368
00:34:03,286 --> 00:34:05,438
- I have one.
- Then, you know.

369
00:34:06,088 --> 00:34:07,496
I wanted to...

370
00:34:09,224 --> 00:34:10,848
Ask you about this.

371
00:34:13,906 --> 00:34:16,756
She received that from Henrik,
the Christmas before.

372
00:34:18,982 --> 00:34:21,775
I studied it more times
than I can say.

373
00:34:23,338 --> 00:34:26,294
-  I know every page of it.
- The last page I’m curious about.

374
00:34:26,295 --> 00:34:27,609
As was I.

375
00:34:27,610 --> 00:34:30,922
List of Names, Numbers and..
Must have some significance.

376
00:34:30,957 --> 00:34:33,124
They’re local phone numbers.

377
00:34:33,159 --> 00:34:35,654
The first belonged to a woman
called Margot,

378
00:34:35,689 --> 00:34:38,450
whose mother was Magda,
who denied she didn’t know Harriet.

379
00:34:38,485 --> 00:34:41,748
The fourth, R.L., belonged to
Rosemarie Larsson,

380
00:34:41,783 --> 00:34:44,649
an elderly woman who died
some years before.

381
00:34:45,734 --> 00:34:49,491
The other three were not connected
in any way that I could find.

382
00:34:50,723 --> 00:34:53,551
I’ve reminded you of things you’d
rather forget.  I’m sorry.

383
00:34:54,197 --> 00:34:55,585
I can’t forget it.

384
00:34:57,272 --> 00:34:59,050
It’s my "Rebecka Case".

385
00:35:00,232 --> 00:35:01,979
I don't know what that is.

386
00:35:02,014 --> 00:35:06,486
Every policeman has at least
one unsolved case to obsess over.

387
00:35:07,338 --> 00:35:10,044
Back then we had an Officer,
Torstensson.

388
00:35:10,079 --> 00:35:13,250
Year after year he kept
going back to his "Rebecka Case".

389
00:35:13,285 --> 00:35:16,251
taking out the files -
studying them over and over.

390
00:35:16,862 --> 00:35:19,141
We were young, we laughed at him.

391
00:35:19,176 --> 00:35:21,143
That was also a missing girl case?

392
00:35:21,178 --> 00:35:23,426
No, no, no. That’s not why I mention it.

393
00:35:24,073 --> 00:35:26,649
I'm talking about the soul
of a policeman.

394
00:35:27,590 --> 00:35:30,104
Poor old Torstensson never solved it,

395
00:35:30,139 --> 00:35:32,394
and he never let it go.

396
00:35:40,110 --> 00:35:41,863
How’s Mr. Palmgren doing?

397
00:35:42,616 --> 00:35:44,547
I heard he had a stroke of some kind?

398
00:35:45,760 --> 00:35:47,062
That's Terrible.

399
00:35:47,915 --> 00:35:50,136
What exactly do you do at this
security company?

400
00:35:50,950 --> 00:35:52,817
Make coffee and sort mail.

401
00:35:52,852 --> 00:35:54,238
But not full-time.

402
00:35:55,089 --> 00:35:56,837
Not even part-time consistently.

403
00:35:56,872 --> 00:35:59,734
They somehow got
along without coffee or mail

404
00:35:59,769 --> 00:36:01,179
in July and August?

405
00:36:06,628 --> 00:36:08,693
- How much did you made there?
- Enough.

406
00:36:10,519 --> 00:36:12,828
- How much is your rent?
- I pay my rent.

407
00:36:16,939 --> 00:36:18,701
And when was the last time you were late?

408
00:36:18,736 --> 00:36:20,118
Never.

409
00:36:21,135 --> 00:36:23,820
Do you think that ring in your eyelid
makes you attractive?

410
00:36:26,942 --> 00:36:28,243
Here’s the problem.

411
00:36:29,727 --> 00:36:32,137
There a discrepancy..

412
00:36:32,172 --> 00:36:34,908
between the obligation of
Mr. Palmgren’s guardianship

413
00:36:34,943 --> 00:36:36,714
and the management of your finances.

414
00:36:36,749 --> 00:36:38,482
There's no discrepancy or a problem.

415
00:36:38,517 --> 00:36:41,007
It was clear to him
I could manage myown finances.

416
00:36:41,008 --> 00:36:42,446
- But that’s not clear to me.
- I’m not a child.

417
00:36:42,448 --> 00:36:44,277
No.  You’re not.
But you were.

418
00:36:44,312 --> 00:36:48,240
And between then and now -
you're committed to a ward at  St. Stephens,

419
00:36:48,275 --> 00:36:50,786
where you continued to display
a violent aggression -

420
00:36:52,479 --> 00:36:55,335
And you failed to adapt to four foster homes

421
00:36:55,371 --> 00:36:58,631
arrested twice for intoxication,
twice for narcotics

422
00:36:58,666 --> 00:37:02,560
again for an assault: smashing
a bottle smashed into a man’s face.

423
00:37:02,596 --> 00:37:04,520
And that's not even that long ago.

424
00:37:05,323 --> 00:37:08,763
You may have conned Mr. Palmgren into
thinking you’ve changed, but

425
00:37:09,835 --> 00:37:11,865
looking at this...

426
00:37:11,900 --> 00:37:14,860
- not to mention how you’re looking
at me now -

427
00:37:15,491 --> 00:37:17,512
I don't think you have.

428
00:37:18,341 --> 00:37:21,098
So the Good
-Old-Mr-Palmgren-Days are over.

429
00:37:21,133 --> 00:37:26,668
Starting now, you’ll be given a monthly allowance.
You’ll provide me with receipts for your expenses.

430
00:37:26,703 --> 00:37:30,189
If the numbers don’t balance, I’ll
have to assume the difference is going to drugs.

431
00:37:30,224 --> 00:37:32,091
I’ve been on myself
since I was ten.

432
00:37:32,126 --> 00:37:33,855
The State- has taken care of you.

433
00:37:33,890 --> 00:37:36,697
Ms. Salander?  Please look at me.
Because this is important.

434
00:37:36,732 --> 00:37:39,725
Since, behavior you’re displaying
right now is elaborately documented here -

435
00:37:39,760 --> 00:37:42,689
- so it would come as a shock to no
one if I chose an alternative to

436
00:37:42,724 --> 00:37:45,702
very lenient arrangement
I've just outlined.

437
00:37:48,800 --> 00:37:53,467
Would you prefer
institutionalization?

438
00:38:13,668 --> 00:38:15,125
- Mikael?
- Yes.

439
00:38:15,160 --> 00:38:16,946
- I'm Liv.
- Hi.

440
00:38:16,981 --> 00:38:18,483
We’re going to the same place.
Hop in.

441
00:38:18,518 --> 00:38:19,965
Okay, thank you.

442
00:38:28,533 --> 00:38:31,884
I found him at death’s door
halfway up the hill.

443
00:38:31,919 --> 00:38:33,327
I’m afraid I’m a bit out of shape.

444
00:38:33,362 --> 00:38:35,590
No, it’s a climb for anyone.
I should’ve warned you.

445
00:38:35,625 --> 00:38:36,936
- Come on in.
- Thank you, Martin.

446
00:38:36,971 --> 00:38:38,354
Henrik says great things about you.

447
00:38:44,176 --> 00:38:46,656
What a place,
look at that view!

448
00:38:46,691 --> 00:38:50,099
I used to work in the company’s
petrochemical division in Goteborg.

449
00:38:50,617 --> 00:38:52,454
When it was sold, I went with it.

450
00:38:52,489 --> 00:38:53,790
A dark day.

451
00:38:54,305 --> 00:38:57,033
I live in Hong Kong now, but come
back to Stockholm for family events,

452
00:38:57,068 --> 00:39:00,015
and when I do, I drive up to spend a
couple days with Martin.

453
00:39:00,050 --> 00:39:03,012
- She comes for the moose steak.
- You can't blame her, it's wonderful.

454
00:39:05,987 --> 00:39:07,309
Something let's open.

455
00:39:08,175 --> 00:39:10,064
Would you like to try something
else?

456
00:39:10,099 --> 00:39:11,722
No, no, no.
It's fine.

457
00:39:17,634 --> 00:39:19,004
You’re writing a book now,
What is it?

458
00:39:19,039 --> 00:39:20,956
- Henrik’s biography.
- I love Henrik.

459
00:39:20,991 --> 00:39:23,279
He’s fascinating.
Martin, too.

460
00:39:23,693 --> 00:39:26,473
Together they’re the
Old Sweden and the New.

461
00:39:26,963 --> 00:39:28,325
They are.

462
00:39:30,223 --> 00:39:31,900
You know about Harriet, right?

463
00:39:33,287 --> 00:39:34,763
- You don’t?
- Yes, I do.

464
00:39:36,314 --> 00:39:37,984
The family doesn’t like
to talk about it,

465
00:39:37,985 --> 00:39:40,419
but it can’t just be
swept under the rug.

466
00:39:40,454 --> 00:39:41,951
- What can’t.
- Harriet.

467
00:39:42,526 --> 00:39:44,403
- We can talk about that  later.
- No.

468
00:39:45,145 --> 00:39:46,447
We can talk about it now.

469
00:39:47,148 --> 00:39:49,281
Liv knows everything about
my crazyfamily.

470
00:39:49,316 --> 00:39:51,977
-  Which is why she’ll never marry me.
- That’s one reason...

471
00:39:52,012 --> 00:39:53,814
I don't wanna read about that
in the book.

472
